FR940902-2-00097 FR940902-2-00048 Determinations Regarding Eligibility To Apply for Worker Adjustment Assistance and NAFTA Transitional Adjustment Assistance In accordance with Section 223 of the Trade Act of 1974, as amended, the Department of Labor herein presents summaries of determinations regarding eligibility to apply for trade adjustment assistance for workers (TA&hyph;W) issued during the period of August, 1994. In order for an affirmative determination to be made and a certification of eligibility to apply for worker adjustment assistance to be issued, each of the group eligibility requirements of Section 222 of the Act must be met. (1) that a significant number or proportion of the workers in the workers' firm, or an appropriate subdivision thereof, have become totally or partially separated, (2) that sales or production, or both, of the firm or subdivision have decreased absolutely, and (3) that increases of imports of articles like or directly competitive with articles produced by the firm or appropriate subdivision have contributed importantly to the separations, or threat thereof, and to the absolute decline in sales or production. Negative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance In each of the following cases the investigation revealed that criterion (3) has not been met. A survey of customers indicated that increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,927; Walker Manufacturing Co., Hebron, OH TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,589; Wordperfect Corp., Oren, UT TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,919; Pennzoil Products Co., Bradford, PA TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,967; AlliedSignal Guidance Control Systems, Lakewood, CA TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,980; Martin Marietta Corp., Government Electronic Systems, Morrestown, NJ In the following cases, the investigation revealed that the criteria for eligibility have not been met for the reasons specified TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,974; Vic Manufacturing Co., Minneapolis, MN The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,854; Infotec Development, Inc., Portland, OR The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,972; Clorox Corp., Jersey City, NJ Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,948; Puritan-Bennett, Boulder, CO Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,055; Portac, Inc., Tacoma, WA Increased imports did not contribute importantly to worker separations at the firm. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,734; Bay, Incorporated (Offshore Division), Corpus Christi, TX The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974 TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,987; Airpol, Inc., Bakersfield, CA The workers' firm does not produce an article as required for certification under Section 222 of the Trade Act of 1974. Affirmative Determinations for Worker Adjustment Assistance TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,779; R. Shrimp, Inc., Aransas Pass, TX A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after March 29, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,778; R & A, Inc., Aransas Pass, TX A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after March 29, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,780; Vikki, Inc., Aransas Pass, TX A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after March 29, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,767; Richard Warren, Inc., New York, NY A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after March 30, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;30,108; Vistalite, Lancaster, PA A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after June 30, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,737; United Industries, Inc., Beloit, WI A certification was issued covering all workers separated on or after March 25, 1993. TA&hyph;W&hyph;29,765; RDEX, Inc., Russell, KS A ce